##11 cases were pathologically dissected and 3 cases were preliminarily diagnosed. mucinous secretion was found in the lung of the deceased

MICRO-SIGNAL BQSHENYIDU

Beijing Youth Daily reports from the official public number

Reporter / Han Qian Wei Xiaohan

Editor / Edward Shek

The Liu Liang team that performed the autopsy

After more than a month of waiting, a team led by Liu Liang, a professor of forensic pathology at the Tongji Medical College, completed the autopsy on Feb. 16 at 3:50 a.m. of the first death from new pneumonia.

As of February 25, the expert team completed a total of 11 cases of new coronary pneumonia death autopsy, of which Liu Liang team responsible for 9 cases, has completed the preliminary diagnosis of 3 cases.

According to Liu Liang, the disease is similar to SARS and has its own characteristics. According to the pathology results so far, some of the deceased's lung sections show mucus discharge, he thinks this is a place to be on the lookout for clinical treatments -- as if "if the mucus doesn't dissolve, oxygen alone may not do the trick, and sometimes it does. ". When positive pressure is applied, it may push the mucus deeper and wider, aggravating the patient's Hypoxia.

Professor Liu Liang and professor Wang Guoping, chairman of the Department of Pathology at Huazhong University of Science and Technology, were interviewed by the media. Next, the expert team will interface the preliminary results of the pathology study with the clinical experts.

To enter the operating room for an autopsy

The donor is at least 52 years old

REPORTER: How is the pathological anatomy of the new coronary pneumonia? How many autopsies have been performed so far? What's the status of the body donor?

Liu Liang: So far from the 16th, our team has dissected 9 cases, and the Shanghai team has dissected 2 cases in Wuhan. The male-to-female ratio of body donors is almost the same, with older donors in their 60s, 70s and 80s, with the youngest aged 52.

REPORTER: In general, how many cases of comprehensive analysis do we need to make to reach a more scientific conclusion?

Wang Guoping: from a scientific point of view, the more the better, a total of 11 autopsy, or to some extent, can explain the problem.

Reporter: Will there be a tendency to look for younger deaths?

Liu Liang: the more pathology cases, the better. Different people have different personality problems, which is to find common problems in personality problems.

We want to see how the virus behaves in different age groups, different genders, and different physical conditions. Which people are susceptible and which people are not, this is definitely going to happen.

Reporter: Where did autopsy work?

Liu Liang: The autopsy was done in the operating room of the hospital. After consulting the family, an autopsy usually begins six to eight hours after the patient's death, sometimes later. All the bodies that have been autopsied are sent to the funeral home by car for cremation.

REPORTER: Before this, still spent a lot of time to apply for research. Is there any improvement in the current research situation and the attitude of the family members?

Liu Liang: Autopsy did spend a lot of time at first, trying to get policy, trying to find a hospital, trying to work with family, so it was relatively hard to get started.

Through media publicity, the family of the deceased also understand the significance of pathological anatomy, a clinician told me that the family acceptance is better than before.

Now, a lot of hospitals are tentatively starting to follow this model, and a lot of hospitals are actively contacting them to do this. I think the future is not only the gold and silver pool and Tongji these two hospitals cooperation, more hospitals will join in.

The pathology researchers studied the samples

There was mucus in the victim's lungs

REPORTER: Are there any cases where pathology studies have been completed? What do you got?

Liu Liang: There are three cases where the preliminary results of the pathological diagnosis have been made, and further examinations, such as immunohistochemistry, special staining, are being done as soon as possible.

As things stand, there are still important findings, but conclusions need to be communicated further with clinical experts to see whether these lesions are caused by clinical treatments or by the disease itself.

Reporter: from the autopsy situation, the new coronavirus in addition to the invasion of the lungs, which organs are affected?

Liu Liang: The pathology of NCP is certainly not only damaging the lungs, but also the immune system and other organs of the body, and the clinician has to be consulted.

REPORTER: Zhong Nanshan said previously, the autopsy of the new coronary pneumonia patients found that the lung is not serious fibrosis, there is a part of the Alveoli, inflammation is very severe, there is a lot of mucus. What does that tell you about the problem? What do these findings mean for clinical treatment?

Liu Liang: under the microscope, we did find mucus on sections of the lungs of some of the victims, which should alert the clinic to this.

The lung in the body is the exchange of oxygen and carbon dioxide place, its function depends on the airway is open, the function of the Alveoli is better. At present, the function of the Alveoli may be damaged, the airway is blocked by mucus, clinical manifestations of hypoxia will appear. So to improve the state of Hypoxia, to keep the airway open, mucus must be diluted or dissolved. The drug is actually already in use, but you can try it again.

In clinical treatment, if the mucus composition does not dissolve, simply using oxygen, may not achieve the goal, sometimes counterproductive. Positive pressure when giving oxygen may push the mucus deeper and wider, will aggravate the patient's lack of oxygen. It's probably something that's been on the clinical radar, but we feel like we need to address it.

REPORTER: Is it possible to identify the exact site of infection and the main target organs of the virus through pathological examination?

Liu Liang: the route of transmission of the virus is not a pathological problem at the moment, we have done nucleic acid tests on different organs and tissues in the previous autopsies, and there are findings that need further analysis, because the results vary from case to case.

REPORTER: Some scholars have raised before, in some patients with severe disease may be an outbreak of Myocarditis or broken heart syndrome, through anatomy, whether this possibility?

Liu Liang: The issue of an outbreak of myocarditis is still up for debate. Broken Heart Syndrome, I'd say less likely.

Reporter: The correlation research shows that the new coronavirus and SARS have a high homology, through the autopsy, now found that the lung performance of the new pneumonia and SARS difference big? What's the difference?

Liu Liang: The new pneumonia is similar to the lesions of SARS, but it has its own characteristics, and we'll do some interpretation later.

Professor Liu Liang, wearing a protective suit, takes part in the autopsy of the first case of new coronary pneumonia

The dissection team is running low on supplies

REPORTER: What difficulties are we still facing in our work?

Liu Liang: it's very important for the autopsy team to protect themselves, which is the equivalent of going to the highest levels of radiation. So far, the protective materials are from other places we "begging" from, hope that more people pay attention to our "special forces.

REPORTER: the Industry Calls for the construction of autopsy rooms meeting the standards of Class A infectious diseases as soon as possible in China's major central cities, and the rules and regulations for the control and prevention of severe infectious diseases should be further improved?

Wang Guoping: The new coronavirus outbreak reminds us that we should attach importance to the construction of the infectious disease, especially the establishment of the standard autopsy room for Class A infectious diseases. This is where we need to draw lessons.

Currently, autopsy rooms that fit this negative pressure of p 2 and P 3 have been seen in Temple of Earth Hospital in Beijing and Guangdong during SARS, but almost nowhere else. The question of the dissecting room should be on the agenda. Failure to meet the standard in the dissecting room can delay the work of the dissection.

This article was first published exclusively by the Beijing Youth Daily in the Toutiao, and is not to be reproduced without authorization.
